According to Alex Montironi the pointing is so bad that if we move the undulators it will contact limit switches - her suggestions to fix this inside
text: The undulators are currently off center. Most of them by 100um, but one by 200um. This is a problem because, if limit switches were not in place, the undulator gap could theoretically contact the beam pipe. To fix this issue: 1.) repoint the undulator such that the Y-pointing isn't so extreme. Maybe down by 400um in Y. 2.) if there is a message in the lower right hand corner of the undulator control panel, follow the common soft line undulator problems wiki to fix the centering. 3.) if there is no message in the lower right hand corner of the undulator control panel, follow theses steps (see pictures below): 1.) go to the VC centering expert display 2.) press the Center VC button Then

title: Other Undulator News
text: Alex also wanted to report a couple important things. Harman Bassan no longer works at SLAC, so, if Alex is not available, the second person to call for undulator troubleshooting is Namrata Balakrishnan. Also, the instances where the upstream HXR undulators don't move and require an IOC reboot is correlated with beam being parked on TD-UNDH. They have a local radiation monitor in place to see if these undulator controls are being damaged by radiation. If we experience difficulty with moving the undulators, it would be good to let Alex or Namrata know if the beam was previously parked on TD-UNDH as another data point in their investigation of this issue.

Notes for weekend and FLEM guide
text: This weekend we want to have the stations all correctly phased, -25 degrees of chirp in L2 (via subboosters), and orbit response data collected for L2, L1, and L3 in that order. Afterward please continue working on threading beam to the dump. Park on TD11 if no bandwidth to work on FACET. After we finish phasing L2 we will need to FLEM. I suggest we put the subboosters to crest, phase all stations in that sector, then put the subbooster back to -25 degrees. When this is done for available stations between 11-4 and 14-6 and the beam is on energy (some steering may be necessary), open FLEM from the MATLAB GUIs. Inside FLEM you'll want to wait until the Data Valid? indicator at the top is green before clicking anything. Then select only L2 (by deselecting L3) and make sure "Use Extant Strengths" is highlighted in the Magnets tab. Then you should be able to scale magnets. You'll probably need to do some steering afterward, and it's highly advisable to save a config in the SCP before embarking on this. Refresher notes for doing orbit response data here: http://physics-elog.slac.stanford.edu/facetelog/show.jsp?dir=/2022/06/11.02&pos=2022-02-11T23:28:31

title: Notes for weekend and FLEM guide
text: This weekend we want to have the stations all correctly phased, -25 degrees of chirp in L2 (via subboosters), and orbit response data collected for L2, L1, and L3 in that order. Afterward please continue working on threading beam to the dump. Park on TD11 if no bandwidth to work on FACET. After we finish phasing L2 we will need to FLEM. I suggest we put the subboosters to crest, phase all stations in that sector, then put the subbooster back to -25 degrees. When this is done for available stations between 11-4 and 14-6 and the beam is on energy (some steering may be necessary), open FLEM from the MATLAB GUIs. Inside FLEM you'll want to wait until the Data Valid? indicator at the top is green before clicking anything. Then select only L2 (by deselecting L3) and make sure "Use Extant Strengths" is highlighted in the Magnets tab. Then you should be able to scale magnets. You'll probably need to do some steering afterward, and it's highly advisable to save a config in the SCP before embarking on this. Refresher notes for doing orbit response data here: http://physics-elog.slac.stanford.edu/facetelog/show.jsp?dir=/2022/06/11.02&pos=2022-02-11T23:28:31 NOTE: LI14 subbooster has sometimes jumped by ~160 degrees. If this occurs you can usually recover energy simply but trimming the subbooster 160 degrees from its current setpoint, but be careful not to FLEM L2 with the subbooster at a kludgy phase as this won't work well.

title: 1st walkthrough done
How to disable the SCP LI11 transverse feedback
text: > FACET/SLC index > FEEDBK System Index (bottom right) > Select LINAC, LI11 FBCK LOOP, then click "Change Loop HSTA" in the bottom right. I forgot to disable this before trying to collect orbit response data and reloading a config did not properly restore the linac orbit. I had to disable the feedback and manually steer the feedback correctors.

title: Matched HXR and SXR complements
Having some trouble with the K scanning GUI
text: RIX changed from 1660 eV to 860 eV, then attempted to use the GUI to move to 870 eV. The energy jumped back to 1660 eV. They went back to 870 eV manually and we restarted the GUI, but when they attempted to scan to 870 eV it jumped again. We are working on troubleshooting this now.

title: Restarted the Matt Gibbs Honorary OPI * Re: Having some trouble with the K scanning GUI
text: It feels as though there is some local reference that does not update, even when the GUI is restarted. For the record, here were the steps I took: -K scanning running just fine with reference set to 1680 eV -RIX requests 860 eV: stop K scanning, change start K -read new reference on GUI, then finalize setup condition, then start listening -RIX requests 870 eV (+10 eV) in GUI, K jumps to 1690 eV (1680 +10 eV, or close to those numbers) -stop listening on GUI, reset undulators to 860 eV, kill GUI -restart GUI, get reference condition, (fix RIX PV), read reference from RIX, finalize setup condition, start listening -same symptoms as before -stopped GUI, reset undulators, then rebooted OPI -restarted GUI with the same steps as before, now it works cc aal

title: NIGHT-Shift Report 2/11-12/2022 Fri-Sat
text: PROGRAM: SPEAR to BEAMS delivering 500mA to users with top-off every 5 mins. BEAMLINES: All open, except BL17. FAULTS: 1930 LN Tank 5B alarm, tank below 100 inches. Silenced and reset fault. Notification sent to Yoli and Tom. 2105 BL16 Pr2 fault sounds B130 alarm and closes beamline. 16-2 WRG1 tripped above 2e-07 Torr trip point. Gauge reading 4.6e-08 Torr on arrival (History Plot shows 2.9e-08 Torr). Fault reset and BL opened 2110. BL16 Allen Bradley clock is slow by 1hr, 10min. EXPERIMENTS: 0005-0110 BL2-1 user support. Users reported failure of cryocon when sample was near 600 Celsius. Upon arrival cryocon was outputting zero current. Did a continuity check of both heating coils. Lower one was ok, top one was broken. Users had a spare coil, I found connection hardware in the BLE lab. Installed new coil, cryocon back online and heating sample as needed. OPERATIONS: 0520 LN tank 5B getting filled at shift change.

Started collecting orbit response data in the physics log: http://physics-elog.slac.stanford.edu/facetelog/show.jsp?dir=/2022/06/12.02&pos=2022-02-12T23:59:59 SBST14 phase jumped by 160deg twice during the early morning. I moved PDES by 160deg, then regolded the SBST before reinstating the -25deg chirp. Ran into instability issues around 10am, couldn't figure out the problem and gave up.

title: Photon folks got the FEE HXR mirrors to move.
Hint of FEL at 18keV not enough for eloss scan. Let MEC know that ST1L0 is still in they will chase down duty tech.
ST1L0...here's a saga for you...
text: Stopper was not permitted since it was missing it's PPS permit due to a CHB fault on the configuration control chassis. Duty tech saw that was due to a latched fault on the associated VAT sensor...which he reset and was able to pull ST1L0. If the sensor trips again while MEC is running, it will dump the VVSs. ...fun!!

title: ST1L0 out reveals TV6L0 vacuum valve in for PIMPs.

text: EPICS says TV6L0 is out, but PIMPs is not seeing that. Some EPICS stuff after TV1L0 looks disconnected. Possibly a vacuum IOC isssue... Calling PCDS...

Completed * CT1701 Close Breaker CT1701-CH by CEFE
XPP VAT sensor found tripped.
text: MEC called informing me that ST1L0 was in. Upon inspection, HUP indicated ST1L0 had NO PERMIT. Due to VAT sensor trip. Reset VAT sensor and pulled ST1L0. ACR reports discrepancy between epics and pimps reading of TV6L0 position. Controls informed and they seem to have been able to fix the problem.

text: I'm going to run it back up with the valves in then open valves to avoid vacuum bursts to the cathode.

title: IPA testing
text: Tested IPAs - have a couple of quick turn-arounds. Just clean, grease and go if 2% is OK.

title: Duty Tech shift change
text: Duty Technician Ydran Willard on duty 14:00 - 00:30.

title: Beam back to TD11 after rephasing 11-1 and 11-2 and restoring BC11 chirp
text: It looks like the phase shifters for these stations jumped this morning for reasons unclear. It also appears that the PDES for these was changed last night. Please refrain from changing these phases as they are controlled in a slightly convoluted way by additional EPICS control and a feedback, all of which get scrambled of the phases are changed. It looks like beam still makes it cleanly to BC14, but is quite low in energy (at least a GeV by rough estimates). Since we scanned all the L2 stations last night I'm surprised by this, but considering the 11-1 and 11-2 jumps there could have been some large phase jumps. I'd suggest trying to get subbooster phase scans once we have bandwidth to work on FACET more. Remember 11-1 and 11-2 are NOT on the LI11 subbooster anymore, so that can be used. Please restore the -25 degrees chirp in L2 after getting back on energy.

text: 1) Salvaged 4 thyratrons and built up 1 more and added to DEPOT. 2) Separated a dozen or so bases and boards to be cleaned up, and then put back together for future thyratrons. 3) Built up 10 installation kits (install paper, hardware kit, and tag) for when new thyratrons are built and ready for installation.
